USA: Repetition is the Mother of Wisdom
It’s funny that Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of the smartest man, as a diligent student repeats on the Afghan issue the strategy of his predecessor, whom he himself took for the most foolish.
When he finally revealed his eagerly awaited Afghan approach, it was shown to be a copy of the script used for Iraq by Bush, created three years ago.
Not only is the phrase “the same as in Iraq” used several times in the same text, but he also did not hesitate to use the title of Bush’s January 2007 statement for his own statement: “A New Way Forward.”
It was he himself who three years ago criticized Bush’s idea of sending new military reinforcements to Iraq, the country that is suffering from civil war, and that criticized him as “an irresponsible decision and with catastrophic consequences.”
The following months, however, showed that Bush’s strategy, based on the recommendations of field captains, was the only possible and successful, so that today nothing is said about Iraq in the news.
Bush's reputation did not improve, yet objectively left his successor in a much more favorable initial situation than expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama expects the miracle to be repeated.
Field captains again asked him to increase the military contingent, especially Commander-in-Chief of Operation General Stanley McCristal, who, despite traditional subordinate relations, subjected the undecided riflemen in the White House to harsh criticism.
He asked for 40,000 men to improve the situation.
The president hesitated for three months, but didn’t come up with anything better, so at least he cheated on the general about 10,000 military personnel.
He managed to get Europe to promise him another 5,000, although he himself previously had at least 10,000.
The most problematic part of Obama’s entire strategy seems to be his goal, to begin withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and to complete this procedure in three years.
Many doubt that the increase will bear the same fruit as the procedure in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars in recent years, Iraq's society is relatively well organized, its leaders respect the agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is different: no one can be trusted and no agreement is met.
Under these conditions it is difficult to prepare Afghan security forces, if they are accustomed to changing the boss every day according to their needs.
The political institutions, although formally established, will remain only a people of Potemkin, after which patriarchal tribal relations will remain.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extraordinarily complicated due to confused relations, even more complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Not even establishing a state that is “actionable,” a minimum goal of the entire operation, seems very real.
The horizon of Obama’s strategy clashes with his voluntarism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has continued to worsen and is now on the verge of erupting.
Only a romantic soul, who knows nothing of reality, can believe that the military sent to war to "come home soon" will do some miracle here.
From a political point of view, setting the date for the withdrawal of troops is purely irresponsible, as the Taliban will regard it as an indirect declaration of American defeat.
The latest NATO summit showed that Europeans are less and less willing to participate in military operations in Afghanistan.
European politicians do not know, nor do they want to explain to their constituents, what the security of Germany or Italy has to do with the Hindu Kush war.
The other factor, capable of radically affecting the situation, is the development of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to get worse and increased sanctions have no effect on the Iranians, the U.S. will have to make a difficult decision: try to solve the problem with military force or not.
It will be necessary to look for answers precisely when, according to Obama, America begins the triumphant withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
However, each such solution will mean a dramatic setback for the Afghan situation.
The only positive point for Barack Obama is the fact that there are three years left before the presidential election and that is why there is still a long time to find another strategy, if it proves to be a total failure.
