This year, women received Nobel Prizes in all categories except physics.
Five women, which is a record number, received this year’s Nobel Prizes in specialized categories and literature from King Charles XVI Gustaf of Sweden in Stockholm today.
In addition to the four scientists, one of the winners was also a German writer of Romanian origin, Herta Müller.
The Nobel Prize in Medicine was awarded to two American biologists, Elizabeth Blackburn and Carol Greider, as well as fellow countryman Jack Szostak for research in the field of chromosomes.
The Nobel Prize in chemistry was awarded to Israeli Ada Jonath and American Venkatraman Ramakrishna and Thomas Steitz for explaining the structure and function of ribosomes.
The last prize, the Nobel Prize in Economics, was awarded to the American Elinor Ostrom and his compatriot Oliver Williamson for the analysis of an economic report.
The only specialized category, without an award-winning woman, was Physics.
This award was received today by scientists Charles Kao for research in the field of optical cables, and George Smith with Willard Boyle for the invention of the CCD chip, which forms the basis of all digital cameras, faxes or telescopes.
Each recipient collected the diploma, the Nobel medal and the certificate of money received.
This sum in each category is up to ten million Swedish kroner (approximately 25 million Czech kroner).
