The study points out that there are many differences in the beginning of cohabitation as a couple and the number of children, depending on whether they work or not and the type of work they develop.
Those who do not have an activity outside the home, work part-time, or have an unstable job, start first living together as a couple, advance the first maternity, and have more children.
In contrast, women in stable employment, mainly in the public sector, delay cohabitation and maternity, and have fewer offspring.
